topics.summary_md:
This is the topic where the two halves of "full-stack" shake hands. Your Spring Boot API serves JSON; `fetch` is how a web page asks for it and shows it to a human.

One idea first: fetching takes time, and JavaScript refuses to freeze the page while waiting. So `fetch()` doesn't hand you data — it hands you a **Promise**, an IOU that data is coming. The cleanest way to work with it is `async/await`, which lets you write waiting code that still reads top-to-bottom.

Make it real with the API you built last module. Say your Spring Boot app serves `GET /api/menu` — this week's mess menu. On the frontend:

```js
async function loadMenu() {
  const res = await fetch("http://localhost:8080/api/menu");
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error("Server said " + res.status);
  const items = await res.json();
  // build <li> elements from items and add them to the page
}
```

Note the two `await`s: one for the response headers to arrive, one for `res.json()` to finish reading and parsing the body. And note the `res.ok` check — fetch does **not** treat a 404 or 500 as an error; it only rejects when the network itself fails. Skipping that check is the most common fetch bug in existence.

Sending data mirrors it: `fetch(url, { method: "POST", headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" }, body: JSON.stringify(data) })`. One speed bump awaits you: the browser will block your page (on one port) from calling your API (on another) until the API allows it — that's **CORS**, fixed in Spring with `@CrossOrigin` while learning. Meeting this error is a rite of passage; now you know its name.

So far your components only know data you typed into the code. Real apps pull data from a server. Two tools make that happen: `fetch` (the browser's built-in way to call an API) and `useEffect` (React's way to run code at the right moment, like "after this component first appears").

The standard pattern:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetch("http://localhost:8080/api/menu")
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => setMenu(data));
}, []);
```

The empty array `[]` means "run once, after the first render." Forget it, and the effect runs after *every* render — and since fetching sets state, and setting state re-renders, you've built an infinite loop that hammers your own API.

Concrete example: the hostel mess menu app. The component renders with an empty list, `useEffect` fires, fetch asks your Spring Boot API for today's menu, the response updates state, and the screen fills in. Notice the timing — there's a moment *before* data arrives. Handle it honestly with three states: loading ("getting today's menu…"), error ("couldn't reach the kitchen — retry"), and data. Apps that skip loading and error states feel broken on hostel Wi-Fi, and interviewers notice when your demo handles them.

This topic is the bridge to Module 11, where the API you call is one you built yourself.
